{"type":"message","id":"f8d80b6f","parentId":"c825bfd1","timestamp":"2026-03-22T20:41:23.477Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There are zero internal edges! All edges go to external nodes. This makes sense - the temporal-attention project is a standalone research project that doesn't import from other local modules. All its imports are from external libraries (torch, numpy, etc.).\n\nSo the causal graph, as built from purely static analysis, has no internal dependency edges within the project. This means `query_impact` will always return nothing for internal entities because there are no internal call edges.\n\nThis is actually a known limitation of static analysis - it only captures what you explicitly import/call, not semantic relationships. The VAE world model is what would capture the *semantic* causal relationships (e.g., \"this function's output feeds into that function's input\" even without an explicit call).\n \nThe static graph is still useful for showing import relationships and basic call graphs, but it's missing the deeper causal structure. The real causal relationships between components would require either runtime tracing or the world model's semantic understanding. For now, I should wrap this up and document the limitation - the graph indexer works but is just limited to static analysis.\n\nLet me test it on a real multi-file project like EXP or mind that actually has internal imports to see if it captures those relationships properly.","thinkingSignature":"bd46697d338e5b1df5c29240bbea04760ce992099cdbe2ce7d823ea8e7d1a629"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_1jvejjqafyg9_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"C:/Users/Zwmar/AppData/Local/Programs/Python/Python312/python.exe C:/dev/code-cause/scripts/index_codebase.py C:/dev/EXP --stats 2>&1"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":52849,"output":315,"cacheRead":12605,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":6