{"type":"message","id":"6a1f6082","parentId":"88243cb4","timestamp":"2026-03-22T20:42:39.674Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to fix the module name computation to replace hyphens with underscores. Also, directories that are Python packages (containing `__init__.py`) should be treated as modules, but directories with hyphens in their names should have those hyphens replaced with underscores.\n\nLet me fix the module name computation and the reference target resolution. The key issue is:\n\n1. When computing the module name from a file path, convert hyphens to underscores\n2. When resolving references to target qualified names, try both the literal name AND the hyphen-converted version\n\nActually, the simpler fix is: when building the module name, replace hyphens with underscores. And when building the reference target qualified names, we need to handle the case where an import like `from kv_evict import BlockManager` refers to a module `kv_evict` that was indexed with a different path.\n \nNow I see the real problem: the `kv_evict` directory lives at `apps/kv-eviction-optimizer/kv_evict/`, but Python imports it as `kv_evict` without the hyphenated prefix. The reference target `kv_evict.BlockManager` needs to be resolvable to the actual indexed node `apps.kv_eviction_optimizer.kv_evict.core.BlockManager`. I need to update the reference resolution logic to try hyphen-converted versions of target names when looking them up.","thinkingSignature":"0860a4c7ace9318e94791928efdf0f0955951759b1190fbdd4d54f4985d1f614"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_fqdexvr4mebb_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:/dev/code-cause/src/causal_indexer/static_analyzer.py","oldText":"        # Compute module name from file path\n        rel = filepath.relative_to(self.root)\n        module_parts = list(rel.parts)[:-1]  # remove filename\n        module_name = \".\".join(module_parts) if module_parts else \"\"\n        self._module_stack.a